{<b>Exercise Eight Answer</b>

1) The first step is to consider your objective.

<i>Your objective is to take 10 tricks with hearts as trump.</i>

2) The second step is to count the number of immediate winners you have, the
number of tricks that you can take without giving up the lead.

<i>There are five immediate winners — one spade,</i> <i>no hearts, three diamonds, one
club.</i>

3) The third step is to identify possible ways to get extra winners.

<i>Ruff two spades in dummy. Promote three tricks in hearts. Length trick in
clubs.</i>

4) The last step is to choose you order of play.

<i>You cannot afford to lead trumps</i> <i>right away for two reasons: (1) you need to
ruff two spades in dummy, so cannot</i> <i>afford to play three rounds of hearts,
which the defenders might do if you lead</i> <i>them; (2) with the club lead, the
defenders threaten to take two club tricks</i> <i>plus their two heart tricks, too
many. You must discard a club loser on the</i> <i>extra diamond winner in dummy, and
ruff spades before leading trumps. The</i> <i>\CA and \DQ will be the two entries to
your hand needed to ruff spades.</i>

<i>Win the \CA. Play the \SA and ruff a spade. Play a diamond to the \DQ, and ruff</i>
<i>your last spade. Play the \DA-K, discarding a club loser. That's seven tricks</i>
<i>in, and nothing can stop you from promoting three more tricks in hearts.</i>}
